<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
The larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eaton" authorityYear="1881" class="Insecta" family="Potamanthidae" genus="Rhoenanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoenanthus speciosus" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="speciosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Rhoenanthus speciosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from those of other 
<taxonomicName authority="(Rhoenanthus)" class="Insecta" family="Potamanthidae" genus="Rhoenanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoenanthus (Rhoenanthus)" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Rhoenanthus">Rhoenanthus (Rhoenanthus)</taxonomicName>
species based on the following characteristics: i) lateral subapical spine of the mandibular tusk present (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Larval morphology (head and mandibular tusk) A Potamanthus formosus Eaton, 1892 B Rhoenanthus magnificus Ulmer, 1920 C R. obscurus Navas, 1922 D angle measurement of mandibular tusk E R. distafurcus Bae &amp; McCafferty, 1991 F R. speciosus Eaton, 1881." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1067.72779.figure10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604591" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">10F</figureCitation>
), ii) absence of medial rounded setae on the mandibular tusk, iii) length of the mandibular tusks ca 1.7-2.3
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of the head, iv) length of the foretibiae ca 1.2-1.23
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of the forefemora and about 2.72-2.82
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
length of the foretarsi, v) leg with colour marking as in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Larval morphology (foreleg) A Potamanthus formosus Eaton, 1892 B Rhoenanthus magnificus Ulmer, 1920 C R. obscurus Navas, 1922 D R. distafurcus Bae &amp; McCafferty, 1991 E R. speciosus Eaton, 1881. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1067.72779.figure11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604592" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">11E, and vi</figureCitation>
) 4 or 5 bipectinated lateral setae on the mandibles (
<bibRefCitation author="Bae, YJ" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" refId="B1" refString="Bae, YJ, McCafferty, WP, 1991. Phylogenetic Systematics of the Potamanthidae (Ephemeroptera). Transactions of the American Entomological Society 117(3/4): 1-143." title="Phylogenetic Systematics of the Potamanthidae (Ephemeroptera). Transactions of the American Entomological Society 117 (3 / 4): 1 - 143." year="1991">Bae and McCafferty 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Egg</emphasis>
(dissected from mature larva). Oval; with two large conical polar caps, (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. SEMs of egg structures of Rhoenanthus speciosus Eaton, 1881 A general outline of egg B micropyle." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1067.72779.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604594" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">13A</figureCitation>
); chorion with numerous scattered tubercles, with knob-terminated coiled threads at the equatorial zone; tagenoform micropyle; sperm guide circular (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. SEMs of egg structures of Rhoenanthus speciosus Eaton, 1881 A general outline of egg B micropyle." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1067.72779.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604594" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">13B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Narathiwat and Songkla provinces.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Remark.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
The larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eaton" authorityYear="1881" class="Insecta" family="Potamanthidae" genus="Rhoenanthus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoenanthus speciosus" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="speciosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Rhoenanthus speciosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bae, YJ" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" refId="B1" refString="Bae, YJ, McCafferty, WP, 1991. Phylogenetic Systematics of the Potamanthidae (Ephemeroptera). Transactions of the American Entomological Society 117(3/4): 1-143." title="Phylogenetic Systematics of the Potamanthidae (Ephemeroptera). Transactions of the American Entomological Society 117 (3 / 4): 1 - 143." year="1991">Bae and McCafferty (1991)</bibRefCitation>
based on specimens from Indonesia and Malaysia. 
<bibRefCitation author="Parnrong, S" journalOrPublisher="Science Asia" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="407 - 409" refId="B18" refString="Parnrong, S, Buathong, M, Sites, RW, 2002. New records of Behningiidae, Potamanthidae, and Prosopistomatidae (Ephemeroptera) from Thailand. Science Asia 28: 407 - 409" title="New records of Behningiidae, Potamanthidae, and Prosopistomatidae (Ephemeroptera) from Thailand." volume="28" year="2002">Parnrong et al. (2002)</bibRefCitation>
reported this species from Songkhla province (southern Thailand). In the present study, we found the larva of this species in the nearby Narathiwat province. The distribution of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="R." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="R. speciosus" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="speciosus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">R. speciosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be restricted to the south of the Isthmus of Kra, as was found for another mayfly species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lieftinck" authorityYear="1932" class="Insecta" family="Prosopistomatidae" genus="Prosopistoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Prosopistoma wouterae" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wouterae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Prosopistoma wouterae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Boonsoong &amp; Sartori, 2019). These findings constitute the northern limit of the known distribution of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
